Definition: Metagenome assembled genome (MAG) identifier for all metagenomic information. The asterisks (*) before and after indicates any unique identification information associated with the bin; see the Bin Id entry for specific details. When these identifiers appear as columns in annotation files the numbers refer to counts of a given gene or annotation in that genome.
Number of base pairs that were non-standard (e.g. Ns). This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of contigs within the metagenomic assembled genome (MAG) (typically matches the # scaffolds). This column header is the default output for CheckM.
The number of genomes used in CheckM completeness assessments. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
The number of marker sets used in the CheckM analyses. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
The number of marker genes used in CheckM analyses. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of predicted genes. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of scaffolds within the metagenomic assembled genome (MAG). This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of marker genes matched 0 times. This column header is the default output for CheckM.

Default column header for Pandas Index in .csv files written by Pandas .to_csv(). For generality Pandas Index values are often read as text. These values are not used in the analysis and are output by default.

Identifier for metagenomic assembled genomes (MAGs) - corresponds to the *bin* column. The contents within the column headers "Genome"; "fasta"; and "Bin Id" are synonymous. The unique identifiers allow data to be connected between different streams. The difference between the headers is due to different sources; the original column headers are maintained in data files to preserve the raw format from the original source. Discrepancies are resolved via script and outputs have consistent column headers. Each identifier has multiple parts separated by underscores or hyphens: (1) river name; (2) year of the study; (3) surface water vs porewater distinction (sw indicating surface water; pp indicating pore water; (4) number in hours; (5) WHONDRS indicating relationship to the Worldwide Hydrobiogeochemistry Observation Network for Dynamic River Systems research consortium; (6) surface water vs porewater distinction (SW indicating surface water; PP indicating pore water); (7) 48  to indicate that the sample is for the 48 Hour study; (8) six digit unique identifier; (9) single letter indicating the method; and (10) bin identifier.

Type of grab sample associated with the solid char sample (300C; 600C; endchar; completecombustion or muffle). "Muffle" means char sample came from material burnt in crucible in a closed muffle furnace. "300C" and"600C" indicates sample was grabbed off the open-air burn table around a temperature of 300 and 600 degrees celcius respectively. "Completecombustion" char samples were ash grab samples from the burn table in-which visually all vegetation had been consumed in the burn. "Endchar" was a homogenized sample of all the remaining char on the burn table after the burn. See BSLE_Burn_Protocol.pdf for more information.

Average upstream depth of stream. Stream depth was averaged on a daily basis over the width and length of the upstream reach as described in Appling et al. (2018b). The dataset is from the Appling et al. (2018c) data release and can be downloaded directly at https://www.sciencebase.gov/catalog/item/59bff507e4b091459a5e0982.
Depth of sensor installation in water column

A time series of the average depth of the reach was created in two steps. First; the average depth of the stream reach was measured via transects; sonar; or public sources. This created a reach-average depth at a single point in time. In order to convert this into a time series; we calculated a time series of depth-offsets based on a single point water pressure datalogger and a local barometric pressure logger. Barometric pressure was subtracted from absolute pressure to get water pressure; which was then converted to depth at a single-point in the stream. The difference between each single-point depth time series measurement and the single-point depth at the reference time (time at which reach depth was measured via transect; sonar; or public sources) was used as the depth offset. This offset for the single-point depth was added to the average stream reach depth to create the time series.

Standard deviation of dissolved oxygen (DO) in percent saturation. Error messages produced by streamMetabolizer. The two errors in this data are "data don't start when expected" and "data don't end when expected". These errors are included when the indicated day does not have a full 24 hours of data. This is often the case for (1) the day of deployment (2) the day of retrieval and (3) partway through deployment. Data was removed partway through deployment when other sampling occurred which disturbed the sensors. The model ignores the data from the days with these errors.

FASTA file analyzed during DRAM annotation. The contents within the column headers "Genome"; "fasta"; and "Bin Id" are synonymous. The unique identifiers allow data to be connected between different streams. The difference between the headers is due to different sources; the original column headers are maintained in data files to preserve the raw format from the original source. Discrepancies are resolved via script and outputs have consistent column headers. Each identifier has multiple parts separated by underscores or hyphens: (1) river name; (2) year of the study; (3) surface water vs porewater distinction (sw indicating surface water; pp indicating pore water; (4) number in hours; (5) WHONDRS indicating relationship to the Worldwide Hydrobiogeochemistry Observation Network for Dynamic River Systems research consortium; (6) surface water vs porewater distinction (SW indicating surface water; PP indicating pore water); (7) 48  to indicate that the sample is for the 48 Hour study; (8) six digit unique identifier; (9) single letter indicating the method; and (10) bin identifier.

Identifier for metagenomic assembled genomes (MAGs) - corresponds to the *bin* column. The contents within the column headers "Genome"; "fasta"; and "Bin Id" are synonymous. The unique identifiers allow data to be connected between different streams. The difference between the headers is due to different sources; the original column headers are maintained in data files to preserve the raw format from the original source. Discrepancies are resolved via script and outputs have consistent column headers. Each identifier has multiple parts separated by underscores or hyphens: (1) river name; (2) year of the study; (3) surface water vs porewater distinction (sw indicating surface water; pp indicating pore water; (4) number in hours; (5) WHONDRS indicating relationship to the Worldwide Hydrobiogeochemistry Observation Network for Dynamic River Systems research consortium; (6) surface water vs porewater distinction (SW indicating surface water; PP indicating pore water; (7)  48  to indicate that the sample is for the 48 Hour study; (8) six digit unique identifier; (9) single letter indicating the method; and (10) bin identifier.

Mean ammonium reported as ammonium (rather than as nitrogen).  5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for ammonium that is appropriate, so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent. For each sampling event (e.g. SPS_005_ION), the NPOC values of each of the three biological replicates (e.g. SPS_005_ION-1; SPS_005_ION-2; SPS_005_ION-3) are averaged. Any replicate values that were identified as an outlier or were above/below the limit of detection are not included in the mean. Outliers were identified using distance based outlier detection. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher, the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean.

If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean.

Any replicate values that were identified as an outlier or were above/below the limit of detection are not included in the mean. Outliers were identified using distance based outlier detection. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean.

The recommendation for numeric data is "-9999" and for character data is "N/A". Some files also use a missing value format specific to when a data value is below the limit of detection or above/below the standard curve. For these cases: a text string is included in the format "[data type]_*|*_Raw_Not_Corrected|*_Final_Corrected" in which the asterisks are the denoted individual data values. See the associated methods deviation (DTL_003) for more details.

Mean daily reach-averaged ecosystem respiration rate (ERtot) in volumetric units. Mean ERtot in volumetric units were calculated for the 356 rivers and streams in the Appling et al. (2018b; 2018c) dataset by multiplying predicted ERtot (in original areal units) by river depth for each daily observation; summing new ERtot daily values (in volumetric units) for each site; and dividing the sum by the number of observations for each site.

Indicator if photo is good based on visual checking. 1 is yes. 0 is no. Photos chosen for visual checking are based on photo resolution uncertainty. High uncertainty resolution photos are checked. The photos that are checked are assigned a value of 0 if they are not good and 1 if they are good. The photos that are not checked (due to low uncertainty) are assumed to be good and assigned a value of 1. Good refers to good for analysis and for machine learning. This assessment is based on skewness of the photo; lack of scale; or large area of non-river objects.
